{"id":"nucl-th/0703086","submitter":"Chhanda Samanta Prof.","authors":"C. Samanta, P. Roy Chowdhury and D.N. Basu","title":"Predictions of Alpha Decay Half lives of Heavy and Superheavy Elements","comments":"18 pages including 5 figures and 1 table","journal-ref":"Nucl.Phys.A789:142-154,2007","doi":"10.1016/j.nuclphysa.2007.04.001","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th astro-ph nucl-ex quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Theoretical estimates for the lifetimes of several isotopes of heavy elements\nwith Z=102-120 are presented by calculating the quantum mechanical tunneling\nprobability in a WKB framework and using microscopic nucleus-nucleus potential\nobtained by folding the densities of interacting nuclei with the DDM3Y\neffective nuclear interaction. The $\\alpha$-decay half lives calculated in this\nformalism using the experimental $Q$-values are in good agreement over a wide\nrange of experimental data. Half lives are also calculated using $Q$-values\nextracted from two mass formulae. The Viola-Seaborg-Sobiczewski (VSS) estimates\nof $\\alpha$-decay half lives with the same $Q$-values are presented for\ncomparison. The half life calculations are found to be quite sensitive to the\nchoice of $Q$-values. Comparison with the experimental data delineates the\ninadequacies of older mass predictions in the domain of heavy and superheavy\nelements as compared to the newer one by Muntian-Hofmann-Patyk-Sobiczewski, and\nhighlights necessity of a more accurate mass formula which can predict\n$Q$-values with even higher precision.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Mar 2007 13:47:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 28 May 2007 09:56:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-06-13"}
